The key insight in this solution is to express $m + n$ in terms of the given congruences. By writing $m + n = 2m - (m - n)$, we can use the given congruences for $m$ and $m - n$ to simplify the expression modulo $14$.
1. Express $m + n$ in terms of $m$ and $m - n$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   m + n &= 2m - (m - n)
   \end{align*}$$

2. Use the given congruences to simplify the expression modulo $14$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   m + n &\equiv 2(4) - (10) \pmod{14} \\
         &\equiv 8 - 10 \pmod{14}
   \end{align*}$$

3. Simplify the result:
   $$\begin{align*}
   m + n &\equiv -2 \pmod{14}
   \end{align*}$$

4. Since the remainder should be non-negative, add $14$ to the result:
   $$\begin{align*}
   m + n &\equiv -2 + 14 \pmod{14} \\
         &\equiv 12 \pmod{14}
   \end{align*}$$
The remainder when $m + n$ is divided by $14$ is $\boxed{12}$.
